data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration needed.** Your code does not use `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt`. The APIs it does use — `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — work identically in .NET 8.

This code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort): You could simplify this with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`, which gives you cleaner code and built-in `CancellationToken` support for future needs:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items,
                         CancellationToken token = default)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, new ParallelOptions
        {
            CancellationToken = token
        },
        item => Process(item, token));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken token)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        Thread.Sleep(100); // or token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(100)
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

But again — this is purely optional. Your existing code requires zero changes for .NET 8.
